    <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="MTA52">
<l>eṇmar patiṉoruva rīraṟuva rōriruvar</l>
<l>vaṇṇa malarēnti vaikalu – naṇṇi</l>
<l>yorumālai yāṟparavi yōvātep pōtun</l>
<l>tirumālaik kaitoḻuvar ceṉṟu</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>As the Eight, the Eleven, the Twelve [and] the Two<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">These groups of deities engaged in worship may be identified as eight Vasus, eleven Rudras, twelve Ādityas and two Aśvin.</note> approach,</l>
<l>offering beautiful blossoms daily,</l>
<l>[and] revere [him] with a singular garland<note xml:lang="en" place="foot">In this context mālai might mean a garland of words, since flowers have already been mentioned in line 2. The Vyākyānam takes it as such and specifies the texts as Puruṣasūkta etc.; in Po. 57, we find an explicit reference using col mālai.</note>, without ever stopping,</l>
<l>they go [and] worship Tirumāl with hands [folded].</l>
      </lg>
    </div>
